There were no significant differences in baseline characteristics between the three vaccine groups (Table 1
). Overall, 861 (88.6%) dogs did not cough, 53 (5.4%) dogs developed a cough at TCHS, and 58 (6.0%) dogs developed a cough at home following adoption. The number of dogs in each vaccine group that coughed within the 30 days post-vaccination was not significantly different (Table 2
). It is interesting to us to note that the incidence of coughing was higher for dogs in their new homes than at TCHS for dogs in the active vaccine groups compared with dogs in the placebo group. During the first 3 days post-vaccination, the cumulative incidence of coughing was also not different among dogs in the three vaccine groups (Table 3
). The cumulative incidence of coughing remained higher for dogs in the IN-BP group than the IN-BPA group, though not significantly so, for the remainder of the 30-day follow-up period (Fig. 1
).
